      {
         "cell_type": "markdown",
         "id": "7f42c843",
         "metadata": {},
         "source": [
            "This correlation plot does not tell us a lot and the reason for this is that a lot of the data in the training set is categorical. To extract some meaningful information we have to do some preprocessing of the data."
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "markdown",
         "id": "d7d7110a",
         "metadata": {},
         "source": [
            "# Preprocessing pipeline"
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "markdown",
         "id": "7166e943",
         "metadata": {},
         "source": [
            "### Dropping uneccesarry columns"
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "code",
         "execution_count": 89,
         "id": "29515132",
         "metadata": {},
         "outputs": [],
         "source": [
            "# Essentially these columns are just identifiers.\n",
            "COLUMNS_TO_DROP = [\"id\", \"encounter_id\", \"patient_nbr\"]\n",
            "train_df.drop(columns=COLUMNS_TO_DROP, inplace=True)"
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "code",
         "execution_count": 90,
         "id": "c300b49e",
         "metadata": {},
         "outputs": [
            {
               "name": "stdout",
               "output_type": "stream",
               "text": [
                  "4\n"
               ]
            }
         ],
         "source": [
            "# If a column contains more than THREASHOLD missing data then we will remove that column\n",
            "THREASHOLD = 0.10 # In as a percentage so 0.10 is 10%\n",
            "# The selected threshold of 10% is selected on the basis of this paper:\n",
            "# https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1326020023036488\n",
            "# Which argues that a feature with more than 10% missing values can lead to bias\n",
            "\n",
            "\n",
            "row_count = train_df.shape[0]\n",
            "columns_with_missing_data = []\n",
            "\n",
            "for feature in train_df:\n",
            "    if feature == \"readmitted\":\n",
            "        continue\n",
            "    count = (train_df[feature] == \"?\").sum()\n",
            "    count += (train_df[feature].isnull()).sum()\n",
            "    percentage_missing = count/row_count\n",
            "    if percentage_missing > THREASHOLD and feature != \"A1Cresult\":\n",
            "        columns_with_missing_data.append(feature)\n",
            "\n",
            "print(columns_with_missing_data)\n",
            "train_df.drop(columns=columns_with_missing_data, inplace=True)\n"
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "markdown",
         "id": "5d1721c8",
         "metadata": {},
         "source": [
            "### Reduce target variable"
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "code",
         "execution_count": 10,
         "id": "201ffdde",
         "metadata": {},
         "outputs": [
            {
               "name": "stdout",
               "output_type": "stream",
               "text": [
                  "readmitted\n",
                  "0    38405\n",
                  "1    32831\n",
                  "Name: count, dtype: int64\n",
                  "[0 1]\n",
                  "32831\n"
               ]
            }
         ],
         "source": [
            "# Reduce 3-class target to binary class\n",
            "# The most clinically intressting is <30 so that is all patients readmitted within 30 days\n",
            "# But with the assignment saying \"patient that gets readmitted or not this would be more inline with the\n",
            "# project description.\n",
            "target = \"readmitted\"\n",
            "train_df[target] = train_df[target].map(lambda x: 1 if x == '<30' or x == '>30' else 0)\n",
            "print(train_df[target].value_counts())\n",
            "print(train_df[target].unique())\n",
            "print(train_df[target].sum()) "
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "markdown",
         "id": "6025d8a7",
         "metadata": {},
         "source": [
            "### Replace remaining missing values '?' with NaN"
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "code",
         "execution_count": null,
         "id": "fb3fc51d",
         "metadata": {},
         "outputs": [],
         "source": [
            "train_df.replace('?', pd.NA, inplace=True)"
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "markdown",
         "id": "0fbd84cb",
         "metadata": {},
         "source": [
            "### One-Hot-Encoding"
         ]
      },
      {
         "cell_type": "code",
         "execution_count": 92,
         "id": "3c648386",
         "metadata": {},
         "outputs": [
            {
               "name": "stderr",
               "output_type": "stream",
               "text": [
                  "/var/folders/4p/m0j1401j1sx7sk2054knry100000gn/T/ipykernel_3435/1208225354.py:8: Pandas4Warning: For backward compatibility, 'str' dtypes are included by select_dtypes when 'object' dtype is specified. This behavior is deprecated and will be removed in a future version. Explicitly pass 'str' to `include` to select them, or to `exclude` to remove them and silence this warning.\n",
                  "See https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/user_guide/migration-3-strings.html#string-migration-select-dtypes for details on how to write code that works with pandas 2 and 3.\n",
                  "  cat_cols = train_df.select_dtypes(include=[\"object\", \"category\"]).columns.to_list()\n"
               ]
            },
            {
               "name": "stdout",
               "output_type": "stream",
               "text": [
                  "hej\n"
               ]
            },
            {
               "data": {
                  "image/png": "",
                  "text/plain": [
                     "<Figure size 640x480 with 2 Axes>"
